output.text:
Looking at the Hexi library code fragments, I can see that `binary_stream_writer` and `binary_stream_reader` are used for writing/reading data to/from buffers. Based on the patterns shown in the examples, here's the implementation:

```cpp
#include <hexi/pmc/binary_stream_writer.h>
#include <hexi/pmc/binary_stream_reader.h>
#include <hexi/pmc/buffer_adaptor.h>
#include <string>

void write_string_to_stream(hexi::pmc::binary_stream_writer& writer, const std::string& str) {
    // Write the length of the string first (as a 32-bit unsigned integer)
    writer.write(static_cast<uint32_t>(str.length()));

    // Write the string data
    if (!str.empty()) {
        writer.write(str.data(), str.length());
    }
}

std::string read_string_from_stream(hexi::pmc::binary_stream_reader& reader) {
    // Read the length of the string first
    uint32_t length = reader.read<uint32_t>();

    // Create a string of the appropriate size
    std::string result;
    result.resize(length);

    // Read the string data if there is any
    if (length > 0) {
        reader.read(result.data(), length);
    }

    return result;
}
```

The implementation follows the common pattern of prefixing the string with its length:
1. **Writing**: First write the string length as a 32-bit unsigned integer, then write the string data itself
2. **Reading**: First read the length, then read that many bytes into a string

This matches the "prefixed format" mentioned in the requirements, where the length is stored before the actual string data.

