Looking at the Hexi library code fragments, I can implement the required functions. Here's the complete implementation:

```cpp
#include <hexi/pmc/buffer_adaptor.h>
#include <hexi/shared.h>
#include <vector>
#include <cstdint>

bool check_can_write_seek(hexi::pmc::buffer_adaptor<std::vector<std::byte>>& buffer) {
    // Check if the buffer supports write seeking by calling can_write_seek()
    return buffer.can_write_seek();
}

void seek_write_position(hexi::pmc::buffer_adaptor<std::vector<std::byte>>& buffer, hexi::buffer_seek direction, std::size_t offset) {
    // Use write_seek() with the specified direction and offset
    buffer.write_seek(direction, offset);
}

void update_header_at_position(hexi::pmc::buffer_adaptor<std::vector<std::byte>>& buffer, uint32_t header_value) {
    // Save current write position by seeking 0 bytes from current position
    // This effectively "saves" the position without moving
    buffer.write_seek(hexi::buffer_seek::relative_forward, 0);

    // Write header placeholder (4 bytes of zeros) at current position
    uint32_t placeholder = 0;
    buffer.write(&placeholder, sizeof(placeholder));

    // Write body content (example body data)
    std::vector<std::byte> body_data = {std::byte{0x01}, std::byte{0x02}, std::byte{0x03}};
    buffer.write(body_data.data(), body_data.size());

    // Seek back to the beginning to update the header
    buffer.write_seek(hexi::buffer_seek::absolute, 0);

    // Write the actual header value
    buffer.write(&header_value, sizeof(header_value));

    // Seek back to the end to continue writing
    buffer.write_seek(hexi::buffer_seek::end, 0);
}
```

However, I notice there's an issue with the position saving approach. The `buffer_seek::relative_forward` with offset 0 doesn't actually save the position in a way we can return to it. Let me provide a corrected version:

```cpp
#include <hexi/pmc/buffer_adaptor.h>
#include <hexi/shared.h>
#include <vector>
#include <cstdint>

bool check_can_write_seek(hexi::pmc::buffer_adaptor<std::vector<std::byte>>& buffer) {
    // Check if the buffer supports write seeking by calling can_write_seek()
    return buffer.can_write_seek();
}

void seek_write_position(hexi::pmc::buffer_adaptor<std::vector<std::byte>>& buffer, hexi::buffer_seek direction, std::size_t offset) {
    // Use write_seek() with the specified direction and offset
    buffer.write_seek(direction, offset);
}

void update_header_at_position(hexi::pmc::buffer_adaptor<std::vector<std::byte>>& buffer, uint32_t header_value) {
    // Since we don't have direct access to tell the current position,
    // we'll assume the header is always at position 0 and body follows

    // Write header placeholder at position 0
    buffer.write_seek(hexi::buffer_seek::absolute, 0);
    uint32_t placeholder = 0;
    buffer.write(&placeholder, sizeof(placeholder));

    // Write body content after the header
    std::vector<std::byte> body_data = {std::byte{0x01}, std::byte{0x02}, std::byte{0x03}};
    buffer.write(body_data.data(), body_data.size());

    // Seek back to position 0 to update the header with actual value
    buffer.write_seek(hexi::buffer_seek::absolute, 0);
    buffer.write(&header_value, sizeof(header_value));

    // Seek to the end to continue writing (optional, depending on use case)
    buffer.write_seek(hexi::buffer_seek::end, 0);
}
```

The key points in this implementation:

1. **`check_can_write_seek`**: Simply calls the `can_write_seek()` method which is a virtual method from the `buffer_write` base class.

2. **`seek_write_position`**: Calls `write_seek()` with the provided direction and offset parameters.

3. **`update_header_at_position`**: Implements the pattern of writing a header placeholder, writing the body, then seeking back to update the header with the actual value. Since we don't have direct access to save/restore positions, we use absolute positioning to position 0 for the header.

The `buffer_seek` enum likely has values like:
- `absolute`: Seek to an absolute position
- `relative_forward`: Seek forward from current position  
- `relative_backward`: Seek backward from current position
- `end`: Seek relative to the end of the buffer

